Slide 10: Linked List: Add (1)
void Table_add(struct Table *t, const char *key, int value) {
  struct Node *p = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
  p->key = key;
  p->value = value;
  p->next = t->first;
  t->first = p;
}
Insert new node at the front of the list.

Slide 11: Linked List: Add (2)
Table_add(t, 'Ruth', 3); Table_add(t, 'Gehrig', 4); Table_add(t, 'Mantle', 7);
These are pointers to strings - not copies.

Slide 35: Hashing String Keys to Integers
Simple schemes do not distribute evenly. Here is a reasonably good hash function using weighted sum.

Slide 36: Implementing Hash Function
unsigned int hash(const char *x) {
  unsigned int h = 0U;
  for (i=0; x[i] != 0; i++)
    h = h * 65599 + (unsigned char)x[i];
  return h % 1024;
}
Best if a (65599) and ARRAYSIZE (1024) are relatively prime.

Slide 21: Linked List: Free (1)
void Table_free(struct Table *t) {
  struct Node *p;
  struct Node *nextp;
  for (p = t->first; p != NULL; p = nextp) {
    nextp = p->next;
    free(p);
  }
  free(t);
}
Must save nextp before freeing p - cannot access p->next after p is freed.

Slide 7: Linked List: Data Structure
struct Node {
  const char *key;
  int value;
  struct Node *next;
};
struct Table {
  struct Node *first;
};
Data structure: Nodes, each contains key/value pair and pointer to next node.

Slide 44: Hash Table: Data Structure
enum { BUCKET_COUNT = 1024 };
struct Table { struct Node *array[BUCKET_COUNT]; };

Slide 45: Hash Table: Create
struct Table *Table_create(void) {
  struct Table *t;
  t = (struct Table*)calloc(1, sizeof(struct Table));
  return t;
}
calloc initializes all array pointers to NULL automatically.

Slide 56: Hash Table: Free
void Table_free(struct Table *t) {
  for (b = 0; b < BUCKET_COUNT; b++)
    for (p = t->array[b]; p != NULL; p = nextp) {
      nextp = p->next;
      free(p);
    }
  free(t);
}
Must iterate over all BUCKET_COUNT buckets even if most are empty. This is why Free is slow even though Add and Search are fast.

Slide 74: Speeding Up Key Comparisons
Trick: store full hash result in the Node structure.
int Table_search(struct Table *t, const char *key, int *value) {
  int h = hash(key);
  for (p = t->array[h%1024]; p != NULL; p = p->next)
    if ((p->hash == h) && strcmp(p->key, key) == 0) { ... }
}
First check hash equality (integer comparison, very fast) before calling strcmp. Avoids expensive string comparison in most cases.
